      "score": 7,
      "comments": 2,
      "author": "cgrinds",
      "published": "2026-07-03T15:32:37Z",
      "bullets": [
        "The language features Rust-inspired syntax and ergonomics, aiming for a developer experience similar to Rust without its strict borrow checker.",
        "It implements Go-style M:N green threads, providing true concurrent 'goroutines' for highly scalable asynchronous execution.",
        "Memory safety is managed via a Swift-like reference-counting model instead of Rust’s lifetime tracking or Go’s garbage collection."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/security",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "A [non-hybrid tls-mlkem] standard by any other name: How IETF evades responsibility for its actions",
      "url": "https://blog.cr.yp.to/20260702-standard.html",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/munamr",
      "score": 4,
      "comments": 3,
      "author": "JanZerebecki",
      "published": "2026-07-03T13:38:34Z",
      "bullets": [
        "IETF is advancing non-hybrid ML-KEM key exchange for TLS 1.3, omitting classical ECDH fallback against post-quantum algorithm compromise.",
        "Pure ML-KEM deployments lack traditional cryptographic safety nets, risking total compromise if post-quantum lattice assumptions are later proven insecure.",
        "Critics accuse the IETF of using procedural loopholes to standardize non-hybrid PQ codepoints, bypassing established consensus on hybrid deployment safety."
      ]
    },
